{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:38:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13763"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13763"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.12,0.01,0.09,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114829"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2145"},{"type":"tags","id":"2360"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114829"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman, a first-year resident doctor, accidentally sustains a needlestick injury to her left index finger while taking blood from a patient. The source patient is a 42-year-old man who presented to the Emergency Department with fever, abdominal pain and jaundice. His medical history is unknown, but he is cooperative with all Emergency Department clinicians. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe resident has no significant medical history. Her only regular medication is the oral contraceptive pill. She has demonstrated immunity to hepatitis B. On examination, her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a small puncture wound on the pulp of her left index finger with a small amount of blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After first aid, which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obtain blood from the source patient for HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C serology","Commence prophylactic antiretroviral therapy","Arrange for the resident to have a further hepatitis B immunisation","Arrange for the resident to have baseline HIV and hepatitis C serology","Refer to the hospital\u0027s occupational health and safety unit"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immediate management of a needlestick injury involves both caring for the recipient of the injury and assessing the risk of the source patient. The first step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eobtain blood from the source patient to test for bloodborne viruses\u003C/strong\u003E including HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C. This will guide whether post-exposure prophylaxis is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlongside testing the source patient, first aid should be administered to the wound. This involves encouraging bleeding (e.g. by gently squeezing), washing the area with soap and water, and applying a waterproof dressing if needed for a deep wound. These steps help to mechanically clear any pathogen that may have been introduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDepending on the risk assessment of the source patient, \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E with \u003Cstrong\u003Eantiretroviral therapy\u003C/strong\u003E and/or \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatitis B immunisation and immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated to reduce the risk of transmission. However, this is not given routinely for every needlestick injury. Factors such as the source patient\u0027s risk factors and bloodborne virus status need to be considered first. In this case, as the resident has demonstrated immunity to hepatitis B, no further hepatitis B immunisation is required, regardless of the source patient\u0027s hepatitis B status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe injured healthcare worker should have \u003Cstrong\u003Ebaseline testing for HIV and hepatitis C\u003C/strong\u003E with follow up testing at three and six months. However, this is not the immediate priority and can be arranged after the source patient\u0027s risk has been assessed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to the hospital\u0027s occupational health and safety unit\u003C/strong\u003E is important for follow up care and should occur promptly. However, the immediate priority is to assess the source patient\u0027s risk and consider post-exposure prophylaxis if needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate first aid after a needlestick injury involves promoting bleeding of the wound, washing with soap and water, and applying a dressing if needed.","Blood should be taken from the source patient (if known) to test for bloodborne viruses including HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C.","Post-exposure prophylaxis may be indicated depending on the source patient\u0027s risk factors and bloodborne virus status."],"references":["Bowden FJ. Needle-stick injuries in primary care. Aust Prescr 2001;24:98-100. Available at: https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/needle-stick-injuries-in-primary-care","Managing exposures to blood and body fluids or substances. In: Department of Health Victoria [Online]. 2015. Available at: https://www.health.vic.gov.au/infectious-diseases/managing-exposures-to-blood-and-body-fluids-or-substances"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13763"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T17:39:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T17:41:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114829"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr